According to the ANOVA (Table 3
                           ) for emission intensity of CDs-BSA complex and based on the p-values analysis, the simultaneous interaction of the CDs and the BSA concentration was obtained to be not significant and the concentration of BSA is observed to be the most significant factor in the emission intensity of the complex. These observations can be justified by considering Fig. 4
                           a, in which although the CDs concentration influences the emission intensity of the complex inversely, the intensity of emission increases significantly by increasing BSA concentrations. Values of adjusted-R2 and R2 were obtained to be equal to 82.3% and 89.3%, respectively.

According to the ANOVA (Table 5
                           ) for emission intensity of NCDs-BSA complex and based on p-value analysis, only NCDs concentration was the significant factor and the interaction of other variable factors did not have any effect on the emission intensity of the complex. These observations can be justified by considering Fig. 5
                           a, in which the NCDs concentration has shown to negatively affect the emission intensity and is decreased by increasing the NCDs concentration from 115.0 to 400.0 μg/ml. The values of adjusted-R2 and R2 were obtained to be equal to 75.8% and 78.5%, respectively.

According to the ANOVA (Table 7
                           ) for emission intensity of the SNCDs-BSA complex and based on p-value analysis, the first order and simultaneous interaction of SNCDs and BSA concentration factors were not significant in the main response R1, the emission intensity of the complex. However, the second-order interaction of the factors was obtained to be significant. These observations can be justified by considering Fig. 6
                           a, in which the SNCDs and BSA are seen to increase the PL emission only at extremum values of very low and/or very high concentrations. The adjusted-R2 and R2 values were 84.5% and 73.5%, respectively.
